\begin_layout Subsubsection
Minimal Majorana nanowire (
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=0$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider the general system presented initially, a (finite) nanowire
 embedded within a 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-type superconductor enclosing between two insulators, but with an exposed
 length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 that is much smaller that the SC coherence length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\ll\xi$
\end_inset

 such that there are no inner edges and it forms basically a continuum,
 as depicted in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:SCnw}}$
\end_inset

).
 Firstly we consider the special case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=0$
\end_inset

 and thus the order parameter will be constant along the whole system effectivel
y.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The energy spectrums of such a system can then be calculated by solving
 the BdG equations defined by the Hamiltonian in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:H_BdG}}$
\end_inset

) but setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=0$
\end_inset

.
 The algebra is not particularly enlightening so we present here numerical
 results obtained with recourse of Quantica.jl.
 For the sake of completeness and clarity we explicitly write the form of
 the Hamiltonian matrix, being
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc|ccc||ccc|ccc}
2t-\mu & -t &  & V_{\text{Z}} & \frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}} &  & \Delta_{0} &  & \\
-t & \ddots & \ddots & -\frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}} & \ddots & \ddots &  & \ddots & \\
 & \ddots &  &  & \ddots &  &  &  & \\
\hline V_{\text{Z}} & -\frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}} &  & 2t-\mu & -t &  &  &  &  & \Delta_{0}\\
\frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}} & \ddots & \ddots & -t & \ddots & \ddots &  &  &  &  & \ddots & *\\
 & \ddots &  &  & \ddots &  &  &  & \\
\hline\hline \Delta_{0}^{*} &  &  &  &  &  & -2t+\mu & t &  & V_{\text{Z}} & -\frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}}\\
 & \ddots &  &  &  &  & t & \ddots & \ddots & \frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}} & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  &  &  & \ddots &  &  & \ddots\\
\hline  &  &  & \Delta_{0}^{*} &  &  & V_{\text{Z}} & \frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}} &  & -2t+\mu & t\\
 &  &  &  & \ddots &  & -\frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}} & \ddots & \ddots & t & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  &  &  & \ddots &  &  & \ddots
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{\uparrow}(x_{1})\\
\psi_{\uparrow}(x_{2})\\
\psi_{\uparrow}(x_{3})\\
\vdots\\
\hline \psi_{\downarrow}(x_{1})\\
\psi_{\downarrow}(x_{2})\\
\psi_{\downarrow}(x_{1})\\
\vdots\\
\hline\hline \psi_{\downarrow}^{*}(x_{1})\\
\psi_{\downarrow}^{*}(x_{2})\\
\psi_{\downarrow}^{*}(x_{3})\\
\vdots\\
\hline -\psi_{\uparrow}^{*}(x_{1})\\
-\psi_{\uparrow}^{*}(x_{2})\\
-\psi_{\uparrow}^{*}(x_{3})\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

where we defined 
\begin_inset Formula $t\equiv\eta/a_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as the hopping parameter and the (central) differential operators read
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{x}\psi_{\sigma}(x) & \rightarrow\frac{\psi_{\sigma}(x_{n+1})-\psi_{\sigma}(x_{n-1})}{2a_{0}}\equiv\frac{1}{2a_{0}}\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 1 & 0 & ...\\
-1 & 0 & 1 & ...\\
0 & -1 & 0 & \ddots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \ddots
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{\sigma}(x_{1})\\
\psi_{\sigma}(x_{2})\\
\psi_{\sigma}(x_{3})\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right)\\
\partial_{x}^{2}\psi_{\sigma}(x) & \rightarrow\frac{\psi_{\sigma}(x_{n+1})-2\psi_{\sigma}(x_{n})+\psi_{\sigma}(x_{n-1})}{a_{0}^{2}}\equiv\frac{1}{a_{0}^{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
-2 & 1 & 0 & ...\\
1 & -2 & 1 & ...\\
0 & 1 & -2 & \ddots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \ddots
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{\sigma}(x_{1})\\
\psi_{\sigma}(x_{2})\\
\psi_{\sigma}(x_{3})\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_phi_0}}$
\end_inset

) we show the low energy spectrum as a function of the Zeeman field 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 for two different scales of the nanowire's length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 We tune 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 from being a weak field where we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

, up to stronger fields where 
\begin_inset Formula $C<0$
\end_inset

, passing through the topological phase transition at 
\begin_inset Formula $C=0$
\end_inset

 case.
 Starting on the figures corresponding to a large nanowire length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, we see that, looking at Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_phi_0}}$
\end_inset

)(a) for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}>0$
\end_inset

 the system is trivially gapped, having its gap decreasing until it reaches
 zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, and then, for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}<0$
\end_inset

, we see the emergence of two Majorana zero energy modes which are gapped
 from the quasicontinuum due to the topological minigap.
 In Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_phi_0}}$
\end_inset

)(c) we show the wavefunctions' amplitude of these emerging Majorana states
 mainly living at the edges of the nanowire and rapidly exponentially decaying
 into it's center.
 One the other hand, for shorter nanowire lengths, we can see that these
 Majorana bound states hybridize into fermions of oscillatory energy around
 zero with overlapping wave functions.
 The energy of the lowest excitation clearly traces the topological transition
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, producing the phase diagrams show in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_real}}$
\end_inset

)(b) as a function of Zeeman energy 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 and chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\color darkgray
This topological minigap can be shown to be effectively 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-wave thus topologically protected states.
 The Majorana length 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{M}$
\end_inset

, i.e the extension of the Majorana wavefunction, is the coherence length
 corresponding to the minigap, thus becoming smaller for stronger SO coupling.
 The Majorana oscillatory hybridization is thus exponentially suppressed
 by both a strong SO (minigap) and nanowire length.
 In both limits, an exact Majorana topological protected zero mode is recovered
 at each end of the nanowire.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, inspecting the spectrum in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_real}}$
\end_inset

)(*) we see that the role of the SO coupling is crucial for the physics
 of Majorana bound states.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{R}}=0$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}>\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

) the spectrum becomes gapless because the magnetic field is basically destroyin
g the superconductivity and thus no localized MBSs emerge.

\color purple
 
\color inherit
In another matter, and inspecting the spectrum in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_real}}$
\end_inset

)(**), see that if we were to choose a phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\neq0$
\end_inset

, in this specific case 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\pi$
\end_inset

 such that the pairing potential behaves as a domain wall, we can observe
 subgap solution in the trivial phase.
 These states, as discussed in the introduction, corresponding to Andreev
 bound states that emerge due to the quick spatial variation of the order
 parameter
\color blue
.
\end_layout

