\noun default
\color inherit
 and the externally applied magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{x}$
\end_inset

 (which controls the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

), we can control the type of solutions we obtain.
 Specifically, by tuning 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 we can change the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}$
\end_inset

 which controls the number of physical solutions with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re\left\{ \zeta\right\} <0$
\end_inset

.
 All these possible results are compiled in schemes shown in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:sol}}$
\end_inset

), with the additional definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{a^{2}-4m^{*2}C_{0}/(a^{2}+b^{2})}\equiv\sqrt{a^{2}+d}\equiv c$
\end_inset

 for conciseness.
 From the analysis shown in that figure, we see that for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}<0$
\end_inset

 we always obtain three possible physical solution while for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}>0$
\end_inset

 we obtain just two.
 On a related matter, see that we have a total five constrain; two boundary
 conditions at the domain wall, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}(0^{-})=\bar{\Psi}(0^{+})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}\bar{\Psi}(0^{+})=\partial_{x}\bar{\Psi}(0^{+})$
\end_inset

, for the two channels (for a total of four boundary conditions) and the
 additional normalization at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\lessgtr0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}>0$
\end_inset

, since the number of constrains is larger than the number of linearly independe
nt coefficients, there will be no zero energy solution, however, for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}<0$
\end_inset

, we have a total of six coefficients to match meaning that there will be
 a pair of zero-energy Majoranas states.
 Therefore, as we tune 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{x}$
\end_inset

, the SC state in the SM undergoes a phase transition from a SC state containing
 Majorana modes at the junction to an ordinary SC state with no Majorana
 modes at the junction.
 Moreover, see that at the particular case of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, which can be achieved by either tuning 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}^{2}-\mu^{2}=\Delta_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

, it always exists a special solution having 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to the closing of the SC bulk excitations meaning that
 it specifies the phases boundary between TP trivial and nontrivial SC phases.
