\begin_layout Standard
The Andreev spectrum as a function of the order parameters phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 can then be obtained by solving the BdG equations defined by the Hamiltonian
 in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:H_BdG}}$
\end_inset

) in the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\ll\xi$
\end_inset

.
 The algebra is not particularly enlightening so we present here numerical
 results, shown in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_phi}}$
\end_inset

), for different nanowire lengths in the trivial and topological phase and
 in its transition (
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}=V_{C}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two Majoranas at either side of a short junction in the topological
 phase combine into the characteristic low energy ABS spectrum 
\begin_inset Formula $E(\varphi)\sim\cos(\varphi/2)$
\end_inset

 of a topological Josephson junction that vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\pi$
\end_inset

, as shown in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_phi}}$
\end_inset

)(b.I.3).
 This parity crossing leads to a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi$
\end_inset

-periodic ground state when fixing quasiparticle parity, and to the so-called
 topological Josephson effect.
 The exact zero modes correspond to the two outer MBSs, decoupled from the
 two 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

-dependent junction (inner) MBSs for long 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The parity crossing at 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\pi$
\end_inset

 becomes lifted by four-Majorana overlaps for short TS nanowires, that couples
 inner and outer MBSs, thereby destroying the 
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi$
\end_inset

 periodicity under an adiabatic 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(t)$
\end_inset

 such that a non-topological 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

-periodic Josephson effect is restored, as apparent in in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_phi}}$
\end_inset

)(b.II.3).
 
